Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, 29% of the total
The early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday, according to the first preliminary results, brought a noticeable weakening of both parties in the previous grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly heavy losses, with the position of its former chairman, Wilhelm Molterer, seriously on the wane.
In contrast, the leader of the election campaign for the Bund for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Carinthian state governor Jörg Haider, is preparing for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, the Social Democrats (SPÖ) remain the strongest force in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, but compared to the last elections in 2006 they lost 5.5 percent of the vote.
Even worse was the ÖVP, which lost almost nine percent of the vote at 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in Austria's post-war history, and especially for the People's Party, which had called for early elections, this is a truly catastrophic result.
In early July, when the ÖVP had left the coalition, the Volkspartei had a clear lead over the SPÖ.
But the voters probably punished the party for failing the government.
Already in the first reactions to the results there was speculation about a possible resignation of the party chairman and former Vice Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could be the case as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party's executive committee.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the electoral debacle, i.e. to a renewal of the grand coalition of the SPÖ and the ÖVP.
The Social Democrats, however, expressed their fear that the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the FPÖ, which received 18 percent of the vote, and the BZÖ, 11 percent - could lead to a repeat of 1999, when the People's Party and the Populists (at that time the FPÖ were still united, but in 2005 they split from the BZÖ) reached agreements on a joint government, which even triggered sanctions from the European Union.
This is clearly the case for Jörg Haider, who has already declared that he is ready to work with any party and is assuming that he will return to Vienna to take part in Austrian federal politics.
The Greens also entered Parliament, but suffered slight losses and slipped from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably passed the four per cent threshold and therefore did not enter Parliament.
