Turkey is expanding its diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey aspired to join the European Union, the European powers were interested in penetrating deep into Turkey's hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosporus, perhaps just 20 steps into Asia, stands one of the finest relics of this failed imperial endeavor.
Hydarpasha Railway Station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the tour guides tell you.
The building sits on a crumbling end of the platform with a tower at each corner of the front, making it look like some provincial German town hall.
The rocks are filthy.
The whole building is falling apart.
But once you're inside the vaulted ticket office, there's no doubt about the grandeur of the project, whose westernmost entrance was this.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolian-Baghdad Society.
Germany, a latecomer to the imperialist game, had to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East, by means of a train connection to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond to what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperialist ambitions were put to rest during the First World War.
His railroad was attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabs.
The relative isolation of its surrounding region, created by the insurmountable borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
British forces withdrew from Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria .
And there was also bad news for the Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, a munitions train blew up the ornate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly decayed, largely passed over by history.
Today, however, this railway serves, at least symbolically, as a gateway to Anatolia and all east of it, highlighting Turkey's expansion of diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has introduced a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of the neighbouring regions, created by the borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The policy of rapprochement is now in force.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iran and Iraq, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
In order to assess the main features of this new foreign policy, I took the night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit one of the leading foreign policy experts of the AKP, Suat Kiniklioglu, a Turkish Member of Parliament.
The next morning, about eleven and a half hours later, after a bumpy ride on tracks that produced the old world pace in the famous documentary "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is considered the new city for the new secular state project to turn its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, which is known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity.
This has caused a lot of distrust in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to the ACP headquarters, a purpose-built, state-of-the-art stone and steel structure in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-finished shopping malls and pubs where middle managers in suits, both men and women, met to close the first business of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even packed a blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey with its immediate neighbours.
The Cold War was an exception", he tells me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
Nowadays, she has to look east and west at the same time.
It wouldn't be one or the other.
She'd have to do both.
"But surely Turkey could one day", I asked, "be forced to make a choice?"
"Turkey", he said, "did not want to face this decision".
He then made a point which almost everyone I spoke to here made almost routinely: Turkey's relations, not only with the Middle East but also with the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be that Europe as a whole can, in a metaphorical sense, travel east on the same railroad tracks towards Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasa station, after another largely sleepless night, I thought of these two German gentlemen, Mr. Ritter and Mr. Conu, who had watched this structure being built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East might now, in large part, be in the hands of Turkey.
And as I was waiting at the dock for the ferry to take me back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe".
At least at the time, there seemed little doubt as to which continent should claim this fascinating land.
In memory of Vernon Handley and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's musical director since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (call back on September 11) was responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic and Choir.
As part of his music program for the city, he formed his great youth choir, Proteus, the following year.
It was designed for youths up to 21 years of age, but when the choir sang for the last time in 1979, some of us were already in our late 20's - we simply refused to leave the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological shape-shifter) stood for the willingness and ability of the choir to attack any piece of music presented to it, whether it was a madrigal or from the Messiah, whether a capella or with full orchestra.
The musical diversity of such a young choir was often astonishing, always exciting, and was only possible because of the inspiration of that man and his enthusiasm for music, which never waned over the years.
How many times has death stopped us from "letting the music speak for itself"?
He used to say, "The composer knows what he wants".
It's all in the music.
So sing it!"
His way of conducting was absolutely clear and precise, never bossy but never excessive.
No matter how high the musical standard, he always demanded a higher one.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the last two decades, from 1962 to 1982, when he was conductor of the Guildford Philharmonic.
In the last 40 years or so, I've written reviews of over a hundred of his concerts, and I can honestly say that I've never been disappointed by a single one -- often inspired by them.
Tod Handley was that rare combination of greatness and personal modesty.
He abhorred conductors who, he said, simply "dealt with one or two of the world's best-known show-horses".
So many of us will miss him.
