∀Auto-bean', which prevents collisions
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan took inspiration from nature, more specifically from bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot that tracks the flight of bees in a swarm and avoids accidents.
This robot is a bio-mimetic car robot drive or BR23C and represents the first step in accidents prevention technologies.
Engineers from the technical development center of the Nissan Motor Co. have developed this small robot in cooperation with the Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the head of technology PR and R&D brand management, the BR23C is an extension of the four-layer Nissan safety shield.
This robot is supposed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid the collisions.
During flight, each bee builds its own oval-shaped flight space, very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But most importantly, the bee's multifaceted eyes, which can see in all directions at an angle of 300 degrees, allow it to fly undisturbed in its own airspace without interruption.
To simulate the all-round perspective, the engineers developed what is called the Laser Range Finder (LRF).
It detects obstacles up to two metres in front of the BR23C, within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor, which is immediately translated into a collision avoidance signal.
∀The moment it notices an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the flight of the bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at an angle of 90 degrees or more to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference from any other system is that this evasion is completely instinctive.
If it were not, the robot might not be able to react with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles,' explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Mobility Laboratory and the lead engineer on this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot can neither move up or down, nor can it move across; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels, and not in infinite directions and in infinite ways, as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used the rotation function in addition to acceleration and deceleration functions to help the little robot avoid collisions.
∀This device only needs a few seconds every time to process the information and act on it.
It does not require to store either the information or the intuitive logic of the manoeuvres performed, so it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of storage space left.
This may sound surprising, but it's not about the gigabytes, and it's not even about the megabytes of storage.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology which Nissan proposes to introduce in the next ten years in production cars.
The robot is powered by lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than a variety of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future application of this technology could be to integrate the unit with a GPS navigation system via satellite to guide the vehicle to its destination and avoid obstacles in its path.
