The 19 hostages freed in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched an attack on the kidnappers of the 11 tourists and their eight companions who had been captured ten days earlier.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions, who were held captive in the desert for eleven days, were brought back to the Egyptian capital this Monday afternoon, safe and sound.
In the morning they were liberated by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
The hostages, who appeared to be in good health, arrived at the al-Maza military base, next to Cairo International Airport, by a special plane at about 3:30 p.m.
They were taken directly by helicopter to the hospital in Maadi, a foreign-resident neighborhood in Cairo, without being able to speak to the press, for examination.
They are all in 'best health' and no ransom has been paid to the kidnappers,' said Egypt's Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna on the tarmac.
After being captured on September 19 while on a four-wheel-drive safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, in the border area between Egypt, Sudan and Libya, the group of hostages was taken from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and a Romanian woman - and eight Egyptians: two tour guides, four chauffeurs, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptus agency, which organised the safari.
An Egyptian security official said that 30 members of the special forces, from two helicopters, launched the attack at night, just before dawn.
'Shots were fired on both sides and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled,' said the official, who wished to remain anonymous.
He explained that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of the Italian diplomatic service, Mr Franco Frattini, reported from Belgrade, where he is now, on the role played by Italian secret agents and special forces.
'We have to acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men from the intelligence service and the special forces,' he explained without giving further details.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
On the eve of the attack, the Sudanese army claimed to have stopped a vehicle carrying the kidnappers during a patrol, killing six of them, including the leader, who was from Chad, and arresting two others.
The army stated that it was linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Movement for the Liberation of the Sudan (SLA-U), which was immediately denied by the movement.
Letters - The Silent Majority of the Culture
A debate on the financing of culture is making headlines and is a central issue in the current election campaign.
The better.
But one area of our cultural life continues to be forgotten.
Who will stand up and denounce the miserable sums that are given to small museums, archives, archaeological digs or national historical sites that are miserably starving?
What politician will dare to remind the federal government that it neglects its monuments and its culturally significant buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, there are no real laws to effectively protect our cultural heritage?
Did you know that the French government is providing 3.5 million euros for the restoration of the castle of Chinon in the Loire Valley alone?
Our American neighbours have it written in their constitution that the protection of cultural heritage belongs to the culture of the American and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all representatives and all government departments, and that in a mutual agreement.
In Quebec, at the Association of Historical Societies of Quebec, at least 40,000 volunteers, gathered in 211 historical societies, are working hard to study history, to save the many private archives and to preserve the archaeological remains with a few coins.
They are also often the watchdogs of our cultural heritage, protesting with the force of despair when funders and decision-makers unleash their bulldozers on our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When will there be a stage for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalise parts of Fortis Bank
The Benelux countries are planning to partially nationalise the Belgian-Dutch Fortis Bank, which has been in turmoil as a result of the US financial crisis. The three countries will put a total of EUR 11.2 billion at the disposal of the banking and insurance institution, which also has branches in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held high-level meetings over the weekend, together with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commissioner for Competition.
In the euro area, Fortis is the first victim of the international financial crisis, which has been going on for a year, and therefore decisions now taken in connection with the Bank could be precedent-setting.
The decision taken on Sunday night is that all three states will buy their respective shares of the bank at about 49%.
The Bank is likely to sell some of its holdings, notably the insurance business acquired by the Dutch company ABN Amro last year.
Fortis shares started to fall sharply last week, and serious crisis scenarios were already emerging in the second half of the week.
However, analysts agree that the bank, with its 85,000 employees, is too big to fail.
The institute's stock fell 12% on Friday to a 14-year low.
Since January, the value of the stock has fallen by more than two-thirds.
At current share prices, the group's market value is EUR 14 billion, which is unrealistic according to the management.
Management believes that the $700 billion American bailout and the resulting market uncertainty are to blame for the plunge in Fortis's shares.
On Monday, however, prices rose slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the new CEO of the Bank.
The bank was also looking for a private buyer, but no interested party with a factual offer was found.
The Belgian government, however, was eager to reassure investors that they should not be afraid of their money.
So far, there has been no panic among the customers, and the bank's branches have not been raided.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent branches, but also calls leasing companies its own.
Fox in the henhouse
Because of a person's use of medication, life and health insurance companies in America often refuse to contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes which link the use of the drug data to the consent of the person concerned in every case.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we leave the chickens to the fox", says Richard Dick, who developed the program to track prescription data, according to the Washington Post.
Insurance companies set the fees and the amount of compensation in the event of damage depending on the health of the customer, and if the risk is overestimated, the insurance will not be taken out at all.
In the past, the customer was sent for a medical examination and the contract was concluded only after the results of the examination were known.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much more economical method: using the customer's identification number, he collects the last one and a half years' data from pharmacies, i.e. which preparations were bought, and the program calculates from this, what disease the customer suffers from and what his state of health is.
For example, if he regularly takes large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it would suggest that his blood fat levels are unmanageably high, which would automatically put him in a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the programme in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so that the insurers only have to do more paperwork, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the disadvantages is that many drugs can be taken for different purposes, such as migraine and hot flashes, but also for depression.
The latter is a high risk factor from the insurer's point of view, whereas the former is not.
For the collection and processing of data, companies have been formed which ask the patient for his consent before obtaining the data.
Now they are required by law to do so, although there has never been a penalty for failure to do so.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory tests and combine them with data on the use of medication, thus providing a more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and at the same time it is becoming more difficult to control how it is used.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect is limited to healthcare providers and insurance companies.
The bill has already been submitted to Congress, which would allow the authorities to control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard realizes that this is not enough, so he wants to further develop his program so that the data can only be shared with the consent of the person concerned.
Another issue, of course, is that the data subject can hardly deny access to his data, otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him.
And so the chickens are left to the mercy of the fox.
