The small plane of billionaire Steve Fossett, which disappeared a year ago, was found
The small plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on a flight over the Nevada desert on September 3, 2007, has been found.
The specimens were found on a high plateau at an altitude of 3,000 m, in the area of the Sierra Nevada Mammoth Lakes between the states of California and Nevada.
However, no human remains were found inside the plane.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson said at a news conference that the plane had been located and that a team had been sent to locate it, and that it was the plane that Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared.
Mr. Anderson also confirmed that no human remains were found on or near the plane.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) reported that a team was dispatched to identify the aircraft, the Bellanca 8kcab, a few hours after it was spotted. The aircraft was lost on 3 September 2007, after Fossett had taken off on a three-hour flight from Yerington, Nevada.
Yesterday, some of Fossett's personal effects were found by a couple near their Mammoth Lakes home.
The documents in question are two identification cards bearing the name Fossetts, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a jacket.
Fossett's search was abandoned a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire had earned a place in history by setting a long string of records.
In 2002, he became the first person to circumnavigate the globe in a hot-air balloon in the sixth attempt: a two-week solo flight.
Three years later, he flew around the world in a single flight without a stopover in an airplane.
Among his many records is a high-altitude flight of 15445 m above the Andes, but this with a co-pilot.
